You float down the stream before lodging in the mud of the bank. A lucky squirel finds you there, burries you, forgets about you. You spend the harsh winter burried in the ground. You freeze, you crack. In the spring, you thaw, and the thaw triggers events within you. You put out a shoot, and it pushes its way up, towards the air, towards the sun. You put out a root, and it digs deep, deeper, seeking the water that will be your lifeblood. You nearly die your first year, uncultivated, uncared for. But in that wild place you cling to life with each stringy root. Your second year is easier. In five years you have grown into a strong tree, producing fruit of your own on your unpruned branches. 
You begin to see more people pass by your glade. The place near the stream where you were planted by an industrious squirel has become a popular picnic spot. On a hot summer day, a small family lays a blanket in your shade. they pick fruit from your branches to eat with their sandwiches. After they eat, the father naps in the shade while the mother cools her feet in the stream. Their two small children explore the glade, gathering rocks and sticks. You watch as they crack open the pits from your fruit, and watch in horror as the youngest places the soft seed into her mouth. Your offspring contains enough cyanide that this afternoon snock could mean the death of both babies. 
